# Frontend Architecture

This rule describes the approved architecture for this project specifically. It supersedes any generic frontend pattern that conflicts with what is written here.

**Rule precedence (full chain):**
`story-driven-development.mdc` → `product-owner.mdc` → `mvp-guardrail.mdc` → `milestone-execution.mdc` → `workflow.mdc` → `coding-standards.mdc` → `frontend-architecture.mdc` (this file) → `testing.mdc`

---

## Folder Structure

```
src/
├── pages/
│   ├── home/
│   │   └── HomePage.tsx
│   ├── configure/
│   │   ├── ConfigurePage.tsx        # Thin route wrapper
│   │   ├── CombinationForm.tsx      # Owns all four inputs and form state
│   │   ├── PrinterSelector.tsx
│   │   ├── MaterialSelector.tsx
│   │   ├── NozzleSelector.tsx
│   │   ├── GoalSelector.tsx
│   │   └── availability.ts          # isAvailable(p, m, n, g) → boolean — no UI
│   └── profile/
│       ├── ProfilePage.tsx           # Thin route wrapper; loads manifest entry by slug
│       ├── ProfileCard.tsx
│       ├── DownloadButton.tsx
│       ├── ImportGuide.tsx
│       ├── FeedbackPrompt.tsx
│       └── importGuides.ts           # Slicer-specific import step copy
│
├── shared/                           # Design system only — zero product logic
│   ├── SegmentedSelector.tsx
│   ├── SearchableDropdown.tsx
│   └── PageLayout.tsx
│
├── lib/
│   ├── manifest.ts                   # loadManifest, findManifestEntryBySlug, cache reset
│   ├── slug.ts                       # encode/decode combination slugs
│   └── url-params.ts                 # parse /configure query params
│
├── styles/
│   └── global.css                    # Global typography, layout, buttons, cards — imported in main.tsx
│
├── types.ts                          # ALL domain types and constants — one file
├── App.tsx                           # Router only
└── main.tsx                          # Vite entry; imports global.css
```

**Boundary rules:**

- Feature components live inside their page directory. There is no `features/` directory.
- `src/shared/` components have zero knowledge of domain entities. `SegmentedSelector` does not know it is displaying materials. Domain labels are applied at the page layer.
- Global navigation lives in `PageLayout.tsx` (header and footer links). Navigation contains no business logic — route matching and active-state styling only. Pages remain route-owned; page-specific wayfinding (e.g. profile breadcrumbs) lives in the page component.
- `src/types.ts` imports from nothing in the project. It is the dependency root.
- `scripts/engine/types.ts` contains engine-internal types only. It never imports from `src/`.
- There is no `src/hooks/` directory at MVP. Shared hooks are added when a second consumer exists.

---

## Routing

Three routes. Configured in `App.tsx`.

```
/                       → HomePage
/configure              → ConfigurePage
/profile/:slug          → ProfilePage
```

`App.tsx` is router configuration only (~15 lines at MVP). It does not need to be split into `router.tsx` and `providers.tsx`.

---

## Global Navigation

Persistent header and footer navigation live in `PageLayout.tsx`. All three routes wrap their content in `PageLayout`.

| Location | Links | Active state |
|---|---|---|
| Header | Home (`/`), Generate Profile (`/configure`) | Current route highlighted; profile pages highlight Generate Profile as the parent section |
| Footer | Home, Generate Profile | No active styling |
| Profile breadcrumb | Home → Generate Profile → Profile | Current page (`Profile`) marked with `aria-current="page"` |

Navigation uses React Router `Link` / `NavLink` primitives. No dropdown menus, no global state, no business logic. Styles are in `src/styles/global.css`.

---

## Page Structure

**Page components are thin route wrappers.** `ConfigurePage.tsx` and `ProfilePage.tsx` render the layout wrapper and their primary feature component. `ProfilePage` owns manifest loading for the slug param.

**`CombinationForm.tsx`** is the only component that owns the full combination selection state (all four inputs). It:
- derives the slicer format from the selected printer
- derives the resolved slug from all four inputs
- controls the generate button state
- delegates navigation on submit

**`availability.ts`** is a module, not a component. It exports `isAvailable`, `isMaterialAvailable`, and `isNozzleAvailable`. It delegates manifest loading to `lib/manifest.ts`. It has no UI and no React dependency.

---

## State Ownership

The URL is the single source of truth for the current combination.

| State | Owner | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| Form inputs (4 values) | `CombinationForm` local state | Initialized from URL query params on mount |
| Slicer format | Derived from printer in `CombinationForm` | Not shown in the UI at MVP |
| Combination manifest | Module-level cache in `lib/manifest.ts` | One fetch per page load; never re-fetched |
| Profile entry lookup | `ProfilePage` local state | Loads manifest, finds entry by slug |
| Profile static data (title, highlights, file path) | Manifest entry on Profile page | Served as static JSON from `/combinations.json` |
| Confidence count | Static placeholder in `ProfileCard` | Stats API deferred post-launch — shows "New profile — be the first to report results" |
| `showImportGuide` | `ProfileCard` local state | Set via `DownloadButton` `onDownloadStarted` callback on first download |
| Feedback prompt | Always rendered on Profile page | Visible on page load; not gated by download |
| Feedback outcome | `FeedbackPrompt` local state | Shows confirmation on submit; POST to `/api/feedback` |

**There is no global store.** Zustand is not installed and is not used at MVP. If a component needs state, it owns it locally. The conditions for a global store — shared UI state across multiple routes, user account state — do not exist at MVP.

---

## Async Data at MVP

All runtime data fetching uses plain `fetch`. There is no React Query / TanStack Query dependency.

| Data | Loader | Pattern |
|---|---|---|
| Manifest | `lib/manifest.ts` | Module-level cache; used by `availability.ts` and `ProfilePage` |
| Feedback submission | `FeedbackPrompt` | Fire-and-forget POST; no loading UI |

Do not add a data-fetching library until a second async requirement with refetch or cache invalidation exists (e.g. post-launch stats endpoint).

---

## Manifest Consumption

`generated/combinations.json` is copied to `public/` during `build:profiles` and served as a static file. It is the source of truth for which combinations are available and their metadata.

**How it is consumed:**

```typescript
// src/lib/manifest.ts
let manifestCache: Manifest | undefined = undefined;

export async function loadManifest(): Promise<Manifest> {
  if (!manifestCache) {
    const response = await fetch('/combinations.json');
    if (!response.ok) throw new Error(`Failed to load manifest: ${response.status}`);
    manifestCache = (await response.json()) as Manifest;
  }
  return manifestCache;
}
```

```typescript
// src/pages/configure/availability.ts
export async function isAvailable(printer, material, nozzle, goal): Promise<boolean> {
  const m = await loadManifest();
  return m.combinations.some(
    c => c.printer === printer && c.material === material &&
         c.nozzle === nozzle && c.goal === goal && c.isAvailable,
  );
}
```

The manifest is loaded once per page session and held in a module-level variable. No React state wrapper is needed for a static file.

---

## API Boundaries

Two runtime API routes exist at MVP (plus a health check):

| Endpoint | Method | Called from | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| `/combinations.json` | GET (static) | `lib/manifest.ts` | Served from CDN/static host — not a server route |
| `/api/feedback` | POST | `FeedbackPrompt` | Returns `{ ok: true }` on success |
| `/health` | GET | Ops / load balancer | Returns `ok` — API server liveness |

**Deferred post-launch:** `GET /api/profile/:slug/stats` and a confidence-count hook. Not implemented at MVP.

**There is no `api` module abstraction.** One POST endpoint does not justify a typed wrapper. Calls are made with plain `fetch` at the call site.

**There is no `/api/generate` endpoint at MVP.** Slug construction happens client-side in `CombinationForm`. The slug is deterministic: `[printer]-[material]-[nozzle]-[goal]`. The form validates against the manifest client-side before navigating.

### Server feedback persistence (not frontend concern)

Feedback is persisted server-side via `FeedbackRepository`. The frontend POSTs to `/api/feedback` and does not know which storage backend is active.

| Env var | Values | Default |
|---|---|---|
| `FEEDBACK_STORE` | `file`, `sqlite` | `file` |

Swap strategy: implement `FeedbackRepository`, wire in `create-feedback-repository.ts`. **SQLite is an implementation detail behind FeedbackRepository.** No handler or frontend changes required.

